column67: The organizational overhead outweighs the benefit. The continual changes in processes and requirements is frustrating. And largely, we've come to the point where we host almost all our own infrastructure. For Brigade, we don't see many benefits.
column69: We love the booth space at KubeCon (though we only get it for Helm, not Brigade). But for many other things, it feels like our projects have to compete with 3rd party products (non-CNCF) for "room on the stage". Webinars are a great example. With Brigade, we don't feel like we get any "native" support. And we suppose that is due to it being a sandbox project.
column71: We have gone from very happy with CNCF to neutral about CNCF. The reasons are largely that the process burden has gone up, we've ended up having to host most of our own infra, and the TOC/SIG reorganization is just not helpful to us at all. It is nice to get the recognition of being a CNCF project, but we are questioning whether that is worth the trade-off. We'd like less process. We'd like it if the SIGs de-emphasized their role as "overseeing" projects (which seems to entail believing they can tell us what to do). We had envisioned CNCF as a place where high quality projects could pool resources and IP. Instead, we feel like CNCF is increasingly becoming an extra "management chain" that we have to report to.

column67: I would recommend the CNCF for a few reasons. First, the technical vetting and due dilligence for a project to be accepted is great and puts a stamp of approval and trust on a new project.  Second, the marketing and visibility from the CNCF is really good and gets the project to a broader audience.  This worked great for Rook since we were a very early project, perhaps more recent projects are having a different experience that could perhaps be more diluted with the higher number of projects.  That is probably counter-balanced though by the improved processes, programs, tooling, support, etc. that the CNCF provides.  All of that has come a long way and is really quite good now.

column71: The CNCF is a good group of hard working individuals with good intentions. In my experience, the CNCF is organized around a set of loose principles with a fairly distributed governance model. This is both good (inclusive) and bad (there's a lot of sprawl/scope).    As with many things, you get from CNCF what you put in. As a startup, it's hard for us to heavily resource CNCF-related work. My suggestions:    - have a technical person (or two, or three) work in marketing. It's clear that there's a gap in technical knowledge (e.g., the CNCF survey has technical errors -- why is Netflix Zuul a service mesh? From the Zuul website: "Zuul is a gateway service that provides dynamic routing, monitoring, resiliency, security, and more."  - staff a technical doc team that can write blog posts on CNCF technology -- imagine if graduated projects got 1 blog post/month; incubation projects got 1 blog post/quarter; sandbox projects got 1 blog post every 6 months; etc. this would help educate users.  - I think the real value CNCF can provide is connecting community members with each other (e.g., we'd love to find more maintainers). that hasn't happened.
